Binary Classifcation:¶

Binary classification is used to predict the probability that a piece of equipment fails within a future time period - N. N is determined by the business problem and the data at hand, usually in consultation with the domain expert.

In binary classificaiton technique, two types of class examples are identified. A positive class, which indicates a failure is associated with label = 1 and a negative class, which indicates normal operations of machine is associated with a label = 0. The idea is to figure out how accurately each model can identify which case each asset/equipment belong to given a particular time period X.

Label construction for binary classification¶

The question here is: "What are the chances/probability that the assets or equipments will fail within the next N cycles/time period" . The labels are classified as per records prior to the failure of an asset i.e assets within N cycles of failure as "about to fail" (label = 1), and records above N cycles are labelled as being "normal" (label =0). In our case of binary classification, the chosen value for N is equal to a window size of 30

  • label 1 - If machine is about fail in the next 30 days -i.e its RUL lies within 0-30 cycles
  • label 0 - If the machine will work normally within the next 30 days .i.e RUL lies above 30 cycles window

Nasa dataset¶

In our dataset class balance between label1 and label0 is imbalanced which is likely to happen in real world .As run to failure experiments to get failure data is rare and failure incidents occur rarely compared to normal working conditions . Class imbalance can lead to higher misclassification rates of models.

As of scikit-learn version 0.18 and above, there is an option to choose a cost function or specify weights for the target class values or target probailities.It can be specified to each model initiation that has the parameter "class_weights". It can accept values as a dict or one can specify the keyword - balanced to let the model balance class weights based on the frequency

**model = model( class_weights = { 0: {weight_values} , 1: {weight_values} } )**

This allows us to tune the model towards get accurate predictions for the failure events. Class weights can be tweaked so as to tune the classifier to give accurate predictions based on requirements

Based on the following article and sklearn documentation we can figure the classifier metrics according to various thresholds thereby allowing us to tune the classifier as per the business requirement

For Example,

In classification of the two labels with respect to our dataset, we arrive at a consfusion matrix as follows

  • True Positive (TP): engines need maintenance and identified by model correctly.
  • True Negative (TN): engines work normal and not classified as failure by the model.
  • False Positive (FP): engines work normal but misclassified as failure by the model.
  • False Negative (FN)" engines need maintenance and not identified correctly by the model.
###### Ideal classification scenario
  • more accurate True positive classes - machines will fail within in stipulated RUL.
  • more accurate True Negatives - machines are not misclassified as failed when they are normal.

def plot_sensor_histogram(sensor ,xlimit,sensor_name,plotname):
    fig, ax1 = plt.subplots(1, 1, figsize=(16,4))
    """ Create sensor_healthy_subset to hold the first few rows of the sensor values 
         when the engine cycle starts from 1
         According to a research paper this is where the sensor values actor normal
         we will label it as healthy state
    """
    sensor_healthy_subset = df_train.groupby('id').head(30)[sensor]
    
    """ Create sensor_failing_subset to hold the last few rows of the sensor values 
         when the engine cycle is reaching its degradation/failure state
         According to a research paper this is where the sensor values actor abnormal
         we will label it as failing state
         
    """
    sensor_failing_subset = df_train.groupby('id').tail(30)[sensor]
    
    # Now we shall plot the histogram of the healthy and failing state of the sensors across all engine's cycles
    sensor_healthy_subset.plot(kind='hist', bins=15, label='Healthy', xlim = xlimit ,color='green', alpha=0.5, ax=ax1)
    sensor_failing_subset.plot(kind='hist', bins=15, label='Failing',xlim = xlimit, color='red', alpha=0.5, ax=ax1)
    ax1.set_title('sensor'+" "+sensor+' -- '+" "+ sensor_name, fontsize=18)
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()
    fig.savefig("images/"+plotname,transparent=False, dpi=100, bbox_inches="tight")

Evaluation of classifier metrics¶

Accuracy¶

Accuracy is calculated as the number of all correct predictions divided by the total number of the dataset. The best accuracy is 1.0, whereas the worst is 0.0

Sensitivity or Recall or True Positive Rate¶

Recall is calculated as the number of correct positive predictions divided by the total number of positives. It is also called recall (REC) or true positive rate (TPR). The best sensitivity is 1.0, whereas the worst is 0.0.

Specificity or True Negative Rate¶

Specificity (SP) is calculated as the number of correct negative predictions divided by the total number of negatives. It is also called true negative rate (TNR). The best specificity is 1.0, whereas the worst is 0.0.

Precision (Positive predictive value)¶

Precision (PREC) is calculated as the number of correct positive predictions divided by the total number of positive predictions. It is also called positive predictive value (PPV). The best precision is 1.0, whereas the worst is 0.0.

False positive rate¶

False positive rate (FPR) is calculated as the number of incorrect positive predictions divided by the total number of negatives. The best false positive rate is 0.0 whereas the worst is 1.0. It can also be calculated as 1 – specificity.

Matthews correlation coefficient¶

The Matthews correlation coefficient is used in machine learning as a measure of the quality of binary (two-class) classifications. It takes into account true and false positives and negatives and is generally regarded as a balanced measure which can be used even if the classes are of very different sizes

F1- Score¶

The F1 score can be interpreted as a weighted average of the precision and recall, where an F1 score reaches its best value at 1 and worst score at 0.

ROC AUC¶

Compute Area Under the Receiver Operating Characteristic Curve (ROC AUC) from prediction scores.It allows for interpretation of how much area under the curve a model covers with respect to all the class lables in classification (binary or multiclass).values near to 1.0 is higher and values closer 0 are understood to be poor classification

def classifier_metrics(model,estimator,actual,y_pred,y_score):
    # Calculating the classification metrics -
    # Input - model predicted values and probablilites
    class_metrics ={
                        'Accuracy' : metrics.accuracy_score(actual, y_pred),
                        'Precision' : metrics.precision_score(actual, y_pred),
                        'Recall' : metrics.recall_score(actual, y_pred),
                        'F1 Score' : metrics.f1_score(actual, y_pred),
                        'ROC AUC' : metrics.roc_auc_score(actual, y_score),
                        'Matthews Correlation Coefficient': matthews_corrcoef(actual,y_pred)    
                      }

  
    df_metrics = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(class_metrics, orient='index')
    df_metrics.columns = [model]
    
    print('\n'+ model +'  Metrics:')
    
    print(df_metrics)
    # Calculating and displaying confusion matrix for each model
    print('\nConfusion Matrix:')
    skplt.metrics.plot_confusion_matrix(actual, y_pred)
    return  df_metrics

def plot_roc(model,title):
    # input - model estimator and title to save plot
    
    # Calculate the probabilites of predicted values - probability of belong to a class 0 or 1
    model_proba = model.predict_proba(X_test)
    
    fig = plt.figure()
    
    ax1 = fig.add_subplot()
    
    skplt.metrics.plot_roc(y_test,model_proba ,figsize = (15,7),title_fontsize='large',text_fontsize='large')
    
    plt.savefig('images/binaryclassification/'+title, transparent=False, dpi=80, bbox_inches="tight")  
    
    return None

def plot_learning_curve(estimator, title, X, y, ylim=None, cv=None, scoring=None, obj_line=None,
                        n_jobs=1, train_sizes=np.linspace(.1, 1.0, 5)):
    """
    Generate a simple plot of the test and training learning curve.

    Parameters
    ----------
    estimator : object type that implements the "fit" and "predict" methods
        An object of that type which is cloned for each validation.

    title : string
        Title for the chart.

    X : array-like, shape (n_samples, n_features)
        Training vector, where n_samples is the number of samples and
        n_features is the number of features.

    y : array-like, shape (n_samples) or (n_samples, n_features), optional
        Target relative to X for classification or regression;
        None for unsupervised learning.

    ylim : tuple, shape (ymin, ymax), optional
        Defines minimum and maximum yvalues plotted.

    cv : int, cross-validation generator or an iterable, optional
        Determines the cross-validation splitting strategy.
        Possible inputs for cv are:
          - None, to use the default 3-fold cross-validation,
          - integer, to specify the number of folds.
          - An object to be used as a cross-validation generator.
          - An iterable yielding train/test splits.

        For integer/None inputs, if ``y`` is binary or multiclass,
        :class:`StratifiedKFold` used. If the estimator is not a classifier
        or if ``y`` is neither binary nor multiclass, :class:`KFold` is used.

        Refer :ref:`User Guide <cross_validation>` for the various
        cross-validators that can be used here.

    scoring : string, callable or None, optional, default: None
              A string (see model evaluation documentation)
              or a scorer callable object / function with signature scorer(estimator, X, y)
              For Python 3.5 the documentation is here:
              http://scikit-learn.org/stable/modules/model_evaluation.html#scoring-parameter
              For example, Log Loss is specified as 'neg_log_loss'
              
    obj_line : numeric or None (default: None)
               draw a horizontal line 
               

    n_jobs : integer, optional
        Number of jobs to run in parallel (default 1).
        
        
    Citation
    --------
        http://scikit-learn.org/stable/auto_examples/model_selection/plot_learning_curve.html
        
    Usage
    -----
        plot_learning_curve(estimator = best_estimator, 
                            title     = best_estimator_title, 
                            X         = X_train, 
                            y         = y_train, 
                            ylim      = (-1.1, 0.1), # neg_log_loss is negative
                            cv        = StatifiedCV, # CV generator
                            scoring   = scoring,     # eg., 'neg_log_loss'
                            obj_line  = obj_line,    # horizontal line
                            n_jobs    = n_jobs)      # how many CPUs

         plt.show()
    """
    from sklearn.model_selection import learning_curve
    import numpy as np
    from matplotlib import pyplot as plt
    
    plt.figure()
    plt.title(title)
    if ylim is not None:
        plt.ylim(*ylim)
    plt.xlabel("Training examples")
    plt.ylabel("Score")
    train_sizes, train_scores, test_scores = learning_curve(
        estimator, X, y, cv=cv, scoring=scoring, n_jobs=n_jobs, train_sizes=train_sizes)
    train_scores_mean = np.mean(train_scores, axis=1)
    train_scores_std  = np.std(train_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_mean  = np.mean(test_scores, axis=1)
    test_scores_std   = np.std(test_scores, axis=1)
    plt.grid(True)

    plt.fill_between(train_sizes, train_scores_mean - train_scores_std,
                     train_scores_mean + train_scores_std, alpha=0.1,
                     color="r")
    plt.fill_between(train_sizes, test_scores_mean - test_scores_std,
                     test_scores_mean + test_scores_std, alpha=0.1, color="g")
    plt.plot(train_sizes, train_scores_mean, 'o-', color="r",
             label="Training score")
    plt.plot(train_sizes, test_scores_mean, 'o-', color="g",
             label="Cross-validation score")
    
    if obj_line:
        plt.axhline(y=obj_line, color='blue')

    plt.legend(loc="best")
    return plt

def threshold_adjust(model,title,fbeta):
    #input - model estimator and title to save plot
    fig = plt.figure(figsize = (8,6))
    ax1 = fig.add_subplot(1,1,1)
    ax1.set_title('Threshold Plot for'+title,fontsize=20)
    ax1.set_xlabel('Discrimation Threshold',fontsize=16)
    ax1.set_ylabel('Score',fontsize=16)# Evaluate the model on the test data
    ax1.tick_params(labelsize=12)
    ax1.legend(loc ='lower left', fontsize='large')
    cv = StratifiedKFold(5)
    visualizer = DiscriminationThreshold(model,cv=cv,argmax='fscore',
                                     fbeta=fbeta,random_state=42,ax=ax1,n_trials = 5)
    
    visualizer.fit(X_train, y_train)  # Fit the training data to the visualizer
    visualizer.finalize()
    
    fig.savefig('images/binaryclassification/'+title, transparent=False, dpi=80)                 
    
    return None

def precision_recall_metrics(model,y_test,y_pred,y_score,title):
    
    # input - model estimator, predicted values, predict probabilites or decision values & title

    # PRecision recall curve metric - output gives model tradeoff between precision & recall
    
    # thresholds - decision threshold - classfiy data with respect to precision/recall
    
    precision, recall, thresholds = metrics.precision_recall_curve(y_test, y_score)

    thresholds = np.append(thresholds,1)
    #queue -queue rate determines the % of number of engines that represent class 1 - need maintenance
    queue_rate = []  
    for threshold in thresholds:  
        queue_rate.append((y_score >= threshold).mean())

    queue_rate = np.array(queue_rate)

    precision_recall = {
                    'Threshold' : thresholds,
                    'Precision' : precision,
                    'Recall' : recall,
                    'Que' : queue_rate
                 }

    df_precision_recall = pd.DataFrame.from_dict(precision_recall)
    df_precision_recall['model'] =model 
   
    fig, ((ax1, ax2)) =  plt.subplots(nrows=1, ncols=2) 
    fig.set_size_inches(18,10)
    ax1.plot(recall, precision, color='navy', lw=2, label='Precision-Recall curve')
    ax1.set_xlim([0.0, 1.0])
    ax1.set_ylim([0.0, 1.05])
    ax1.tick_params(labelsize=16)
    ax1.set_xlabel('Recall',fontsize=20)
    ax1.set_ylabel('Precision',fontsize=20)
    ax1.legend(loc="lower left", fontsize='large')

    ax2.plot(thresholds, precision, color='red', lw=2, label='Precision')  
    ax2.plot(thresholds, recall, color='green',label='Recall') 
    ax2.plot(thresholds, queue_rate, color='blue',label='Engines') 
    ax2.set_ylim([0.0, 1.05])
    ax2.tick_params(labelsize=16)
    ax2.set_xlabel('Threshold',fontsize=20)  
    ax2.set_ylabel('%',fontsize=20)
    ax2.legend(loc='lower left', fontsize='large')
    plt.savefig('images/binaryclassification/'+title, transparent=False, dpi=80, bbox_inches="tight") 
    return df_precision_recall

Future Steps:¶

Classification Thresholds

https://blog.insightdatascience.com/visualizing-machine-learning-thresholds-to-make-better-business-decisions-4ab07f823415

By varying thresholds for all the classifiers we can arrive at a business calculation such that at a give time and business decision we can decide which model gives the best business value. Its applicable mainly for binary classification only. We can vary thresholds to achieve better recall rate than precicion to prevent misclassification of engines that are failed as normal. This way we can tune the model better to achieve max profit. The above two links give an idea of how to proceed with this.

Questions : Whats the cost that we can assume to calculate the above expected value for classification True Positive (TP) - model selecting the engines that need maintenance correctly. True Negative (TN) engine normal condition False Positive (FP) - enginer normal but model says failure False Negative (FN) engine failure but model says working normal

When we assign a cost to these classification output we can arrive at a profit calculation that can help further in selecting the best model
